Problem I Faced
While building a UI using a Column, I needed to conditionally render multiple widgets based on different flags.
At that time, I wasn’t aware that Flutter supports inline if conditions inside widget lists. To handle conditions, I used ternary operators like:

condition
  ? CustomWidget()
  : SizedBox.shrink()

Since there were multiple conditions, the widget tree ended up with a lot of unnecessary SizedBox.shrink() placeholders, making the code:
Hard to read
Verbose
Slightly inefficient

I learned that Dart supports collection if and the spread operator (...), which allows cleaner conditional rendering directly inside widget lists.

Improved Approach Using Spread Operator
Instead of adding empty widgets, I rewrote the code like this:

Column(
  children: [
    if (condition1) ...[
      CustomWidget1(),
    ],
    if (condition2) ...[
      CustomWidget2(),
    ],
    if (condition3) ...[
      CustomWidget3(),
    ],
  ],
)

What Changed
Removed unnecessary SizedBox.shrink() usage
Cleaner and more readable widget tree
No extra invisible widgets in the layout
Better aligned with Flutter’s declarative UI style

The spread operator (...) allows inserting multiple widgets into a list conditionally, making UI code significantly cleaner and more maintainable.

Takeaway
Whenever dealing with conditional UI in Flutter, prefer using collection if + spread operator instead of fallback widgets like SizedBox.shrink().
This leads to cleaner, more expressive, and production-ready code.
